To live in a declining city, yet make one's home in virtue;
To retire from the ways of the world, and cultivate the waters;
To rule a country with art, and live as a wandering scholar by the wayside;
To be prosperous in dangerous times, and to be renowned in peaceful times;
To govern the people, or not to cultivate the fields;
To have a mind like a mountain, yet to be unclear in one's intentions;
To live in a peaceful land, yet not to observe the virtues;
To have wisdom like water, yet to be unaware of the currents;
To have virtue as a cloud, and to control the winds of the wilderness;
To have faith and to honor the country, and to use power as a source of faith.

The servant speaks:
I have not yet understood the ways of the gentleman.
